fields.description:
Every now and then over the past couple of weeks, I've found my CC inexplicably shut down and exhibiting the following message in cc.log:

{quote}
2013-04-10 13:16:29  INFO 000010669 ccCheckState             | this cluster controller marked as shut down
{quote}

A restart of the CLC seems to bring the CC back up.

I've attached logfiles from the CC and CLC.

comments.body:
I've seen smilar problem on my cloud. Changing priority to blocker.
The last log messages before CC halts are:
{code}
2013-04-22 18:23:37  INFO 000014408 ccCheckState             | this cluster controller marked as shut down
2013-04-22 18:23:37 ERROR 000014408 monitor_thread           | ccCheckState() returned failures
{code}

I don't see anything interesting in {{cc.log}}. There is, indeed, one outage, resulting from a ShutdownService call:

{code}
2013-04-10 13:16:28 DEBUG 000025364 doShutdownService        | invoked: userId=admin
{code}

Nothing corresponding to that in {{cloud-output.log}}, unfortunately, though it is rife with exceptions in {{Topology}}.

From looking at {{handlers-state.c}}
{code}
int doStopService(ncMetadata * pMeta, serviceInfoType * serviceIds, int serviceIdsLen)
{code}

There are two conditions when the CC will enter the {{SHUTDOWNCC}} state:
# {{strcmp(serviceIds[i].type, "cluster") == 0}}
# {{serviceIdsLen < 1}}

Meaning then that the CLC sends that cluster a StopServiceType request which has either: (1) the serviceId set to the cluster or (2) no serviceIds.

In the CLC there are two places which could possibly be sending a StopService request to the CC:

*Cluster state machine* in {{com.eucalyptus.cluster.Cluster.ServiceStateDispatch}}, but it never sends a StopService request (only Start,Enable,Disable).  I don't see how this could be sending it.

*Node state machine* in {{com.eucalyptus.node.NodeControllerConfigurationBuilder.fireStop(ServiceConfiguration)}} and {{com.eucalyptus.node.Nodes.updateServiceConfiguration(ServiceConfiguration, NodeInfo)}}.  In the first case, {{fireStop()}} uses {{com.eucalyptus.node.Nodes.send(ServiceConfiguration, ServiceTransitionType)}} which always sets a specific serviceId which is that of the NC being stopped.  In the second case, {{updateServiceConfiguration()}} uses {{Topology.stop(ncConfig)}} which in turn would be calling {{fireStop()}}.

Looking at the {{handlers-state.c}} code I don't see any other way this could be happening.

What would be useful next is to capture the StopService request arriving.  Also, there may be traces of the request at the {{DEBUG}} log level showing up in {{cloud-cluster.log}}.

Afaict, either there is some unidentified sender of StopService or there is a bug in {{handlers-state.c}}.

I just had a somewhat different episode. This time after 3 migration attempts, the CLC classified my CC as "NOTREADY" and kept it in that state for more than 1 hour although CC operations seemed to be going just fine!!! The CC as not restarted!

{code}
SERVICE	cluster        	PARTI00        	CC_63          	NOTREADY  	37  	http://10.111.1.63:8774/axis2/services/EucalyptusCC	arn:euca:eucalyptus:PARTI00:cluster:CC_63/
{code}
